      "body": "Hi Mark,\r\n\r\nGreat to hear from you, and I’m glad to offer some broad,\r\nnon-case-specific guidance on motion practice.  Below is a high-level\r\nchecklist we follow in-house at Carter & Goldstein, together with a\r\nfew strategic pointers that tend to keep things on track.\r\n\r\n1. Pre-Filing Housekeeping\r\n   • Double-check the controlling rule set (local rules, standing\r\norders, judge-specific procedures) for page limits, word counts,\r\nspacing and font requirements.\r\n   • Calendar every relevant deadline, including any meet-and-confer\r\nor pre-motion conference requirements.  Even where not mandatory, an\r\nearly courtesy call to opposing counsel often streamlines briefing\r\nschedules.\r\n\r\n2. Structuring the Papers\r\n   • Assemble the motion packet in the following order: (a) Notice of\r\nMotion with precise relief sought; (b) Memorandum of Law; (c)\r\nSupporting declarations / exhibits; (d) Proposed order; (e)\r\nCertificate of Service / Compliance.\r\n   • Keep the memorandum tight: a short, neutral statement of facts; a\r\nclear articulation of the legal standard; then numbered argument\r\nheadings that mirror the requested relief.  Judges appreciate a table\r\nof authorities if the brief exceeds 10 pages.\r\n\r\n3. Filing & Service Mechanics\r\n   • E-file before 5:00 p.m. local time to avoid the dreaded\r\n“next-day” docketing date.  Upload exhibits as separate PDFs; label\r\nthem descriptively so chambers staff can find what they need quickly.\r\n   • For sealed material, file a redacted public version\r\nsimultaneously and lodge the unredacted version under seal with the\r\nproper motion to seal.\r\n   • Deliver courtesy copies only if the judge’s rules still require\r\nthem (many have suspended this post-COVID).\r\n\r\n4. Follow-Up\r\n   • Set calendar reminders for the opposition and reply deadlines the\r\nmoment the motion is filed.\r\n   • Track the docket for related filings—sometimes the court will sua\r\nsponte set oral argument or convert the motion to a different\r\nprocedural vehicle.\r\n\r\nStrategic Considerations\r\n   • File sooner rather than later—controlling the briefing schedule\r\ncan freeze discovery on contested issues and shape settlement\r\ndiscussions.\r\n   • If there is any factual dispute, consider attaching a declaration\r\nto blunt the argument that the motion raises matters outside the\r\npleadings.\r\n   • When full relief is a stretch, couple the primary request with an\r\nalternative (e.g., dismissal with leave to amend, or in the class\r\ncontext, strike overbroad subclasses).  This gives the court an\r\n“off-ramp” and often yields at least partial success.\r\n   • A concise, one-page proposed order saves the judge’s clerk\r\nconsiderable time and subtly frames the outcome in your client’s\r\nfavor.\r\n\r\nResources\r\nI’m attaching (separately) two internal, sanitized documents that may help:\r\n   • Motion Filing Procedures – a step-by-step checklist with templates.\r\n   • Successful Motion Example – a redacted brief that illustrates\r\nflow and formatting.\r\n\r\nLet me know if you need anything more granular, and best of luck with\r\nthe matter.\r\n\r\nAll the best,\r\nJane\r\n\r\n—\r\nJane Q. Counsel | Carter & Goldstein LLP\r\n"
